    <statement><p>Find the <m>y</m>-intercept and any <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of the quadratic curve.</p>
<p><m>{y}={-4x-5x^{2}}</m></p>
<p><m>y</m>-intercept: <fillin characters="16" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><m>x</m>-intercept(s): <fillin characters="17" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(-0.8,0\right), \left(0,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>First, we change the equation into standard form:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {y} = {-5x^{2}-4x} }</m></p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into <m>{y}={-5x^{2}-4x}</m>, and we have <m>y=0</m>.</p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,0)</m>.</p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y=0</m> into <m>{y}={-5x^{2}-4x}</m>, and then solve for <m>x</m>.</p>
<p>For this problem, the polynomial can be factored:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = {-5x^{2}-4x} \\
   0 \amp = {-5x^{2}-4x} \\
   0 \amp = -x(5x + 4) \\
   -x = 0     \quad \amp \text{or} \quad 5x + 4 = 0 \\
   x = 0 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad  5x      = -4 \\
   x = 0 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x          = -0.8
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercepts are <m>(-0.8,0)</m> and <m>(0,0)</m>.</p>
</solution>
